    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! Lactic acid is formed in the muscles during high-intensity exercise when the body’s demand for oxygen exceeds its supply. Without enough oxygen, muscle cells switch to anaerobic metabolism, producing lactic acid as a byproduct. The body then gradually clears lactic acid during recovery, converting it back to glucose in the liver in a process called the Cori cycle. With rest, it helps replace spent energy reserves and promotes muscle recovery.",
      "source": "target",
